## Tags and Groups

### Organize By What Matters

Tags are lightweight labels you can create on the fly. Create "volunteer," "leadership," "donor," "invited_to_training"—whatever categories help you segment and communicate. Tags appear on profiles as chips, easily scannable. Add multiple tags to any person, remove tags just as easily.

The tag system enforces workspace uniqueness but allows organic growth. Start with a few core tags, add more as your organizing work evolves. Archive tags that are no longer useful. Filter your entire community by tag combinations to create targeted lists for events or communications.

### Groups for Structure

While tags are informal, groups provide structure. Groups can represent geographic chapters, working committees, affinity groups, or administrative divisions. Each group has members and admins—admins can manage membership and settings, regular members just participate.

Groups support hierarchies. Create parent-child relationships to mirror your organizational structure. A regional group might have multiple local groups beneath it, each with its own membership and leadership.

People can belong to multiple groups simultaneously, reflecting the reality that individuals often participate in multiple parts of an organization. Group membership appears on profiles with admin status clearly marked. Add or remove people from groups directly from their profile, or manage bulk membership from the group page.

